<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Johnnie L. Roberts, a reporter in The Wall
Street Journal's New York bureau, won a John Hancock Award
for Excellence in Business and Financial Journalism.
   Mr. Roberts was honored in the financial-business
newspapers and magazines category for two articles examining
how Dun &amp; Bradstreet Corp. collects and disseminates
information on the credit-worthiness of U.S. companies. The
awards, sponsored by John Hancock Financial Services, include
a $5,000 cash prize.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   L. Gordon Crovitz, assistant editor of The Wall Street
Journal's editorial page, was awarded a 1990 Gerald Loeb
award for editorials on alleged prosecutorial abuses of the
Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations law. The
editorials recently also won a first place award for
commentary from the New York State Bar Association.
   The Loeb awards, which cite distinguished contributions to
public understanding of business and financial issues,
include a $1,000 cash prize. They were established in 1957 by
the late Gerald Loeb, a vice president of E.F. Hutton &amp; Co.,
and are administered by the John E. Anderson Graduate School
of Management at the University of California at Los Angeles.
